# LeakSanitizer suppressions for OpenSSL 3's process-global state.
#
# OpenSSL keeps the implicitly-fetched cipher method (from EVP_*Init_ex) and the
# loaded providers in library-global structures that are released only in an
# atexit handler. On some OpenSSL builds (e.g. Ubuntu's libcrypto.so.3) LSan runs
# its leak check before that handler and reports them as leaks; on others (e.g.
# Fedora's OpenSSL 3.5) the cleanup runs first and nothing is reported.
#
# These are one-time library globals, not driver leaks: aes_cbc/des_cbc free every
# EVP_CIPHER_CTX (src/tns/auth.c), and the legacy+default providers are loaded once
# via pthread_once and intentionally never unloaded (they must stay active for the
# session's lifetime). Both roots below match any frame in the allocation stack, so
# they cover the direct + indirect allocations beneath them without suppressing a
# leak that originates in our own code.
leak:OSSL_PROVIDER_try_load
leak:EVP_CIPHER_fetch
